Date: 27 Feb 2001
From: The Pig Disease Information Centre <pdic@btinernet.com>
Source: Press briefing by Chief Veterinary Officer [edited

Outbreaks 13-16 on farms in Co. Durham, Lancashire, Northampton.
The government is taking powers to close public footpaths.
***
Date: 27 Feb 2001
Source: BBC and a MAFF spokesperson [edited

Outbreak 17 announced by MAFF has occurred at an abattoir in Witton le
Wear, County Durham.
Situation report from MAFF at 1pm today:
(a) Total number of premises placed under restrictions (Form A) because of
suspect clinical disease since the start of the outbreak on 20 Feb 2001 is 78;
(b) Number of premises where Form A restrictions have been lifted following
a full veterinary enquiry since the start of the outbreak on 20 Feb 2001 is
39;
(c) Number of premises on which Foot and Mouth Disease confirmed since the
start of the outbreak on 20 Feb 2001 is 169;
(d) Number of premises remaining under Form A restrictions while
investigations are continuing is 22;
(e) Number of premises where all susceptible livestock have been
slaughtered following confirmation of disease at 24 Feb 2001 is 3;*
(f) Total number of susceptible livestock slaughtered on those premises at
[or? following confirmation of disease at 24 Feb 2001 is 918.*
* This is the information available at 13.00hrs on 24 February. Lines
(a)-(d) may not total because of Form A premises taken as Dangerous Contacts.
Horse racing authorities are ready to cancel all British meetings for the
next week in a bid to counter the spread of the outbreak.
***
Date: 27 Feb 2001
Source: National Pig Association [edited

[The 18th case of FMD [was confirmed at an abattoir in Okehampton, Devon,
tonight.
***
Date: 27 Feb 2001
Source: BBC news & MAFF spokespersons [edited

Livestock movements in the UK are to be banned for a further 2 weeks. Some
strictly controlled movements to abattoirs will be permitted. A 10 mile
exclusion zone, affecting horses as well as farm animals around the
abattoir in Anglesey.
The infected lamb had come from a market in Yorkshire.
The suspect farm in Aberdeenshire has been cleared as the diagnostic tests
are negative.
***
Date: 27 Feb 2001
Source: BBC news 9am [edited

The government is expected to take special powers to close public footpaths
near farms, to reduce risk of spreading FMD virus. Requests for voluntary
avoidance of livestock farms has apparently not been completely successful.
***
Date: Feb 27 2001
Source: National Pig Association [edited

Agriculture Minister Nick Brown has announced the Government is applying
for 152M BPS "agrimoney" compensation for beef, sheep and dairy farmers,
arising from the drop in incomes for the year 2000. 16M would be taken
from future budgets of the pig industry restructuring scheme for those who
need help now.
[In the 1967-68 outbreak of FMD in UK the government paid approximately 125
percent of market value, but it was great incentive for farmers to report
suspected cases. - Mod.TG
***
Date: 27 Feb 2001
Source: National Pig Association [edited

Swill at source farm came from schools (9pm)
---------------------------------
Sunderland City Council is reported to have supplied swill made from school
dinners to the Waugh brothers at Hedon on the wall, but the contract was
terminated in January. The Council is currently trying to establish the
origin of meat served in its schools.
FMD news and overview at: <http://www.pighealth.com>
