[2
Date: 27 Feb 2001
From: Patricia Doyle, PhD <dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
Source: This is North Scotland, 27 Feb 2001 [edited
<http://www.thisisnorthscotland.co.uk/page.asp?t=editorial/news/local/edarti
cle&area=Latest+news&s=edit&opensect=Local%20News&ID=60137>

Scotland was warned it was on the brink of a "Foot and Mouth Disaster" last
night as the crisis deepened with the confirmation of a 12th case of the
disease south of the border.
Government ministers and officials will today discuss the extension of the
current ban on UK livestock movements beyond Friday's original deadline,
although Agriculture Minister Nick Brown told the Commons there could be
some individual movements between farm and abattoir under licence.
The one farm under suspicion in Scotland was this morning awaiting results.
Grampian Country Food Group, which owns Banks Farm, near Fyvie,
Aberdeenshire, were cautiously optimistic the pig farm would be cleared today.
The Government's chief veterinary officer, Jim Scudamore, admitted
livestock farmers may have to suffer the ban on exports for up to 6 months
after the UK is declared free of FMD.
Almost 7000 animals have been or are about to be slaughtered in a bid to
stop the disease, including 1800 cattle, 1600 pigs and 3500 sheep. Mr Brown
said he will announce some form of controlled movement of animals direct
from farms to abattoirs.
If Scotland remain free of the disease, strictly controlled movements of
cattle, sheep and pigs direct from farms to abattoirs may be resumed.
*******
[3
Date: 27 Feb 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: the Irish News, 27 Feb 2001 [edited

The Department of Agriculture last night issued a raft of measures aimed
at keeping Foot-and-Mouth Disease (FMD) out of Northern Ireland.
A number of checks were put in place at Northern Ireland ports and airports
to stop the spread of disease, and Minister for Agriculture Brid Rodgers
said she believes Northern Ireland was FMD-free.
Disinfection facilities have been provided for vehicles at Larne and
Belfast, and travelers have been advised to visit the Department of
Agriculture's veterinary staff if they have visited farms in Britain. All
livestock vehicles will be inspected and sprayed externally with
disinfectant. Any containing horses will be examined and the horses could
also be sprayed in special circumstances.
A complete ban has been placed on the trade of FMD-susceptible animals, and
all animal products will be checked to see if they meet the new stringent
regulations.
